* https://www.chronox.de/jent/index.html
* https://www.chronox.de/jent/index.html#documentation
* https://www.chronox.de/jent/doc/CPU-Jitter-NPTRNG.pdf
* https://web.archive.org/web/20220702110325/https://pthree.org/2016/05/24/cpu-jitter-entropy-for-the-linux-kernel/
* https://packages.debian.org/sid/jitterentropy-rngd

Playing devil's advocate here: Ted Ts'o <ref>He's the main developer behind Linux's RNG and staunchly resisted relying only on Intel's RDRAND. His opinions carry weight with good reason.</ref> expresses strong skepticism about the efficacy of RNGs that rely on CPU jitter. Summary: CPU jitter may not be as random as thought to someone who designed the CPU cache and knows how its internals "tick" <ref>https://lwn.net/Articles/586427/</ref>. So while these RNGs may not harm, another solution for RNG-less platforms may be a good idea.

<blockquote>
It may be that there is some very complex state which is hidden inside the the CPU execution pipeline, the L1 cache, etc., etc. But just because *you* can't figure it out, and just because *I* can't figure it out doesn't mean that it is ipso facto something which a really bright NSA analyst working in Fort Meade can't figure out. (Or heck, a really clever Intel engineer who has full visibility into the internal design of an Intel CPU....)
</blockquote>

